=A0
Good question. Let me give my opinion.

=A0
BACKGROUND=
:

=A0
There are 5 nasals (anunasikas) in Sanskrita - at the end of each gr=
oup (ka-group, cha-group etc). Bindu becomes m before p, ph, b, bh (e.g. sA=
mba, Arambha), n before t, th, d, dh (e.g. anta, sundara), N before T, Th, =
D, Dh (e.g. kaNTaka, brahmANDa).
=A0
There is no nasal corresponding to y, =
r, l, v, sh, Sh, s, h.As someone else said before, bindu is supposed to bec=
ome this gum/gam thing when followed by them. However, what is supposed to =
be a single consonant (nasal) with no life (vowel) of its own and hanging o=
n as an extension at the end of the previous syllable, now becomes a full s=
yllable by itself - a consonant (g), an vowel (u or a or something in betwe=
en) and a nasal (m). It changes the chhandas (metre) by adding an extra syl=
lable. It makes absolutely no sense to me. It is definitely wrong.
=A0
MY T=
HEORY:

=A0
There can be a clue in another tradition in some parts of India=
. The bindu M followed by h in narasiMha or siMhAsan is pronounced by some =
as "ngh" (i.e. narasingha, singhAsan).
=A0
Combining these 2 data points, m=
y theory is that the first nasal, which comes before g, is supposed to be u=
sed before y, r, l, v, sh, Sh, s and h. Over centuries, things got corrupte=
d in Veda chanting and people started saying gum and gam.
=A0
PRACTICAL TIP=
:

=A0
If you take "saMhitA sandhiH" in atharvasheerShaM, I pronounce M as =
the nasal before (g). The only way we can trick our brains to pronounce tha=
t nasal sound is to pronounce it with "g" or "k" following it (as the n sou=
nd in "king", "monkey"). So start pronouncing as though you are going to sa=
y "sanghitA", but skip saying "g" at the VERY LAST moment and jump to hitA.=
 If you skip too early, your brain may not pronounce the nasal correctly. I=
f you skip too late, some amount of g sound may creep in and make it incorr=
ect.

=A0
So you are effectively pronouncing "san(g)hitA", where the sound =
in brackets is not pronounced (silent). If this is too complex for you, I s=
uggest saying "samhitA" or even "sanhitA". It is better than saying "saguMh=
itA" and messing up metre and rhythm.
=A0
Similarly, suppose you have "aMsh=
uH". People say this as "agumshuH". Instead of that, it is better to just p=
ronounce the bindu (M) as m or n and make this "amshuH" or "anshuH". But th=
e best IMHO is to pronounce it as "an(g)shuH". Start pronouncing as though =
it is "angshuH" and skip over g at the last moment.

=A0
I suggest that thi=
s used to be the correct way to pronounce Veda mantras and people misunders=
tood some notations and errors crept in. Similarly, traditions like "narasi=
ngha" and "singhAsan" evolved due to errors creeping in in actually skippin=
g g.

=A0
