=A0
OTHER ERRORS:=

=A0
There are many other common errors in the pronunciation of Sanskrita -=
 even Veda. While I am not an authority, I trust my common sense and am con=
fident that what people are saying now is incorrect. Whether the alternativ=
e I propose is correct or not, common practices are definitely incorrect.
=
=A0
For example, the lifeless consonant hanging on as an extension at the e=
nd of the previous syllable (e.g. t at the end of "prachodayAt") is given l=
ife and made into a separate consonant when it occurs at the end of a line.=
 The word "prachodayAt" is pronounced as "prachodayAtU" by many scholars.Th=
is alters chhandas and makes it meaningless too. 
=A0
Probably some guru di=
d it in the past so that his sishyas could hear the last consonant better a=
nd sishyas learnt it that way and propagated that way. A lifeless consonant=
 is too transient to hear clearly, i.e. prachodayAt, prachodayAk and pracho=
dayAp sound pretty much the same to ears without super-fine attention. So a=
 teacher may intentionally make the last consonant more audible and prolong=
 its life, by adding life (vowel) to it.
=A0
The other corruption is visarg=
a. What is supposed to be merely releasing air from lungs is pronounced var=
yingly as "ha", "hi" or "hu" based on previous sound and a new syllable is =
introduced, breaking chhandas.
=A0
Also, the "ai" and "au" sounds are prono=
unced incorrectly by many Indians, especially southerners. These sounds are=
 supposed to result from pronouncing a+e and a+o (respectively) without a b=
reak. But the way most people pronounce them, that grammar rule does not wo=
rk. If you pronounce them correctly, the grammar rule is spot on!! Please r=
emember that Sanskrit grammar is not arbitrarily decided by someone, but ba=
sed on astute observation of inherent structure.
=A0
Another thing is the r=
u/ri as in rushi/rishi and kruShNa/kriShNa. What is supposed to be an vowel=
 is made into a semi-consonant (r) + another vowel (i or u). That is defini=
tely wrong. If you pronounce this sound correctly and then say a, you are s=
upposed to get ra. The way south Indians say it, you get ru+a=3Drva. The wa=
y north Indians say it, you get ri+a=3Drya. Both are incorrect. Moreover, v=
i in "vikRti" is supposed to be a laghu (short sound). The way people prono=
unce it (vik-ru-ti or vik-ri-ti), it ends up being a guru (long sound). Thi=
s is definitely wrong.

=A0
If you formally studied linguistics and phonolo=
gy, get a feel for the vowel trapezium in your mouth. At its top, you have =
i inside and u outside. You connect them with a line and trisect it. You wi=
ll get i, so called ru/ri, so-called lu and u as the 4 points. By adding a =
to them, you get semi-vowels ya, ra, la and va, respectively. Again, all Sa=
nskrit grammar rules are based on astute observation of inherent structure.=

=A0
There are hardly any people now-a-days who pronounce these ru/ri and l=
u sounds correctly.
=A0
