one is 
written in Devanagari script like "pa" with a cross line through it=
. The
 first letter "sha" (as in shiva) is pronounced by some as "Sha" and =
by 
some as "sa" and both are incorrect.
>=A0
>First some background..
>=A0=

>Consider
 the five Sanskrit letters "ka" (k as in in kavi - poet), "cha" =
(ch as 
in chaNDI or church), "Ta" (T as in Tom or Tapori), "ta" (t as in 
=
tantra) and "pa" (p as an pass). Pronounce them in quick succession a 
few =
times - "ka cha Ta ta pa". Note the point where tongue touches the 
upper p=
alate/surface of mouth when
 you say these. For "ka", it will be way back i=
n mouth, near the throat.
 For "cha", it will move towards the front, but s=
till in the back. For 
"Ta", it will move further towards the front and ton=
gue will touch a 
little above teeth. For "ta", tongue will touch teeth. Fo=
r "pa", tongue 
will not touch anything, but lips will touch each other.
>=
=A0
>Say "ka
 cha Ta ta pa" several times and notice the progression from t=
he back of
 mouth to lips. Get a feel for the position of "cha Ta ta". Say =
"cha Ta 
ta" several times.
>=A0
>Now, the pronunciation of "sha Sha sa" (s=
h as
 in shiva, shrI etc, Sh as in uShA, veSha etc, s as in satya, sama) is=
 
very similar to that of "cha Ta ta". In the latter 3 sounds, tongue 
touc=
hes the upper palate of mouth at 3 places (for which you just got a 
feel).=
 In the former 3 sounds, tongue comes close to touching in the 
same 3 plac=
es, but does not actually touch. It comes close to touching 
and there is s=
ome
 gap.
>=A0
>With this understanding, now practice saying "cha sha" 
sev=
eral times, "Ta Sha" several times and "ta sa" several times. You 
will see=
 that each pair is pronounced at the same place. If tongue 
touches mouth's=
 upper palate at one position for the first sound and 
comes close to touch=
ing at a *different* position for the second sound 
in the same pair, you a=
re making a mistake. Try again.
>=A0
>No wonder
 that visarga becomes sh, S=
h and s if ch, T and t (respectively) come 
after it, as per sandhi rules o=
f grammar. Sanskrit grammar is very 
logical and based on phonology (study =
of sounds).
